title: For Sale:  Adcor Defense B.E.A.R. Elite Piston AR-15   16"
postcontent:
Check around Gunbroker, etc. you will not find a Piston Elite for less than $1800 and many are over $2000, and don't forget shipping and transfer fees on top of that!  Also this rifle has a factory installed 2-stage trigger included.  This is an early serial number (somewhere under 30) and will no doubt become a collector's item increasing in value.  Below are the specs which will explain why this is a revolutionary piston AR.  Regrettably I must sell to fund another purchase.  Nikon M-223 4-16x42 BDC 600 scope and matching mount ($600 value) available for $500.  Face to face cash sale to CCW or other proof of legality of gun ownership required.

B.E.A.R. (Brown Enhanced Automatic Rifle) models from Adcor Defense feature a patent-bearing, gas piston system with a free-floating barrel for increased accuracy. This is due to the piston's incorporation into the
upper half of the forward rail system - so it never touches the barrel.
Extremely close machine tolerances eliminate the need for piston rings. 
With a tool-less field strip design, a B.E.A.R. requires nothing more than
a firing pin to disassemble, yet remains strong. The piston's cyclical rate for a controlled rate of fire adjusts with a turn of the gas plug located in the front piston assembly. Because diminished heat reaches the upper, hot gases and carbon particulates are prevented from entering the receiver, lubricant lasts longer and maintenance is simplified. Due to superior design, the B.E.A.R. has no carrier tilt and low fouling of the chamber and action. The ejection port wiper prevents the entry of dust, sand and other debris by moving into the ejection port opening flush with the inside geometry of the upper receiver. The spring-loaded shield allows the bolt carrier to return to ready position. Being made of a highly-durable, self-lubricating polymer helps the shield withstand temperature extremes.  The B.E.A.R. Elite series features a few upgrades, including a Magpul MOE rifle stock and Magpul MOE ergonomic rifle grip with aggressive texturing for a sure grip. The chrome-lined barrel from FN Manufacturing has 1:7 twist and is hammer-forged with a M249 rifling profile for long life and exceptional accuracy. It also has a forward-placed, ambidextrous charging handle. It has a two-piece key-locked, highly-rigid quad-rail system made of aircraft-grade 7075-T6 aluminum alloy that seamlessly mounts to the upper receiver made from the same aircraft-grade 7075-T6 aluminum alloy.  The upper and lower rails separate with the push of a button - no special tools required.

postcontent:
For sale is a rare factory assembled Maadi Griffin Model 89 .50 BMG that was originally purchased by competitive shooter Carl Matts directly from Maddi-Griffin and used in several long-range competitions before I purchased it directly from him. Typically these rifles were sold as a kit and were assembled by the owner, but Carl originally purchased this rifle for competition and had enough leverage to have the factory assemble it.

He eventually decided to use a different rifle for his competitions and sold this one. This is a great investment rifle, especially since so few of them were produced.

title: For Sale:  VOTE NO ON I-594 IN NOVEMBER OR LOSE YOUR GUN RIGHTS
postcontent:
Unless you want your gun rights to be taken away by a handful of millionaires and billionaires, you will need to talk to everybody you know and ask them to VOTE NO ON I-594 IN NOVEMBER.  Here's why...

September 9, 2014 at 5:36 PM
The Ballmers give another quarter million to support I-594
Posted by Joseph O'Sullivan

Steve Ballmer’s been in the news quite a bit lately: keeping busy with basketball teams (and more basketball teams)  and stepping down from the Microsoft board.

And the former Microsoft CEO and his wife are continuing to add to the big-dollar campaign in support of Initiative 594, which would expand background checks on firearms purchasers. Ballmer and wife Connie each donated $125,000 – for a total of $250,000 – to the Washington Alliance for Gun Responsibility’s independent expenditure group in support of the campaign. The records appeared today on the state’s campaign disclosure website, though the donations are dated Sept. 4.

I-594 would expand background checks past what is currently covered by federal law to include people buying guns online or at gun shows, as well as many personal transfers of guns. The Ballmers have now donated $830,000 to the campaign, which has also seen big donations by Nick Hanauer, Bill and Melinda Gates, Paul Allen and Michael Bloomberg’s gun safety advocacy group.

Opponents of I-594 have called the deep-pocket donors elitists who want to buy an election. Alan Gottlieb, chairman of the Citizens Committee for the Right to Keep and Bear Arms, even challenged Gates to a debate.

Washington Alliance for Gun Responsibility has now raised north of $7.3 million for the initiative, which voters across the state will approve or reject this fall.
